Choose life. Choose the planet you were born on, the one you’re standing on right now. Choose the oceans, the forests, the air you breathe, knowing they need our help now—not some distant planet in the void. Choose caring for Earth instead of dreaming about abandoning it. Choose real solutions here, instead of fantasies of life light-years away.

Choose a billionaire’s dream to escape, to build colonies on red deserts while the blue planet burns. Choose the allure of rockets, headlines, and billion-dollar visions, but ask yourself who really benefits. Choose watching as resources pour into Mars missions while entire cities here are left without clean water.

Choose a vision of humanity where only the wealthy, the powerful, the “innovators” get to imagine a future. Choose to ask yourself who gets to be on those ships, and what’s left for those who can’t afford a ticket. Choose knowing that the “Mars colony” sounds like survival, but for most, it’s just a distraction from problems no one wants to solve.

Choose wondering why we’re so eager to escape a world we haven’t finished building yet. Choose asking why we’re rushing to make a new home while ignoring the harm done to the one we have. Choose seeing Mars not as a dream, but as a reminder of what we’re leaving behind—the inequity, the pollution, the waste.

Or, choose life on Earth. Choose investing in solutions that heal instead of running from problems that we created. Choose valuing the planet that gave us everything before turning to one that offers nothing. Choose caring for all life, not just human survival. Choose staying, building, working together on this world until it’s a place worth keeping.

Choose life—not life on Mars, but a life we can all live, here, where we belong.
